#Approach:

Approach:
Ye code exactly k distinct integers wale subarrays count karta hai using:

Exact(k) = AtMost(k) - AtMost(k - 1)

1. helper(nums, k) count karta hai kitne subarrays me at most k distinct elements hain.
2. Sliding window + HashMap use hota hai:
   - right pointer se current element window me add karte hain
   - map me uski frequency maintain karte hain
3. Agar map.size() > k ho jaaye,
   to left pointer aage badha ke window shrink karte hain
   aur frequencies update karte hain.
4. Har valid window ke liye
   (right - left + 1) subarrays add ho jaate hain.
5. Final answer:
   helper(k) - helper(k - 1)

Main idea:
Exactly k distinct directly count karna tough hota hai,
isliye pehle at most k aur at most k-1 count karke difference le lete hain.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(k)

#Code:

class Solution {

    public int helper(int[] nums, int k){
        int left = 0;
        int right = 0;
        int cnt = 0;
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        while(right < nums.length){
            map.put(nums[right], map.getOrDefault(nums[right], 0)+1);

            while(map.size() > k){
                map.put(nums[left], map.get(nums[left])-1);
                if(map.get(nums[left]) == 0) map.remove(nums[left]);
                left++;
            }
            cnt += (right - left + 1);
            right++;
        }
        return cnt;
    }

    public int subarraysWithKDistinct(int[] nums, int k) {
        int val1 = helper(nums, k);
        int val2 = helper(nums, k-1);
        int result = val1 - val2;
        return result;
    }
}
